docs.abstract: After walking away from a deal, Tesla’s chief agreed to give up the chairmanship for three years and pay a $20 million fine.
docs.snippet: After walking away from a deal, Tesla’s chief agreed to give up the chairmanship for three years and pay a $20 million fine.
docs.lead_paragraph: Elon Musk, under pressure from his lawyers and investors of Tesla, the company he co-founded, reached a deal with the Securities and Exchange Commission on Saturday to resolve securities fraud charges. The settlement will force Mr. Musk to step aside as chairman for three years and pay a $20 million fine.

headline.main: Elon Musk Steps Down as Chairman in Deal With S.E.C. Over Tweet About Tesla
headline.print_headline: Tesla Chief Reaches Deal With the S.E.C. to End A Securities Fraud Case

docs.lead_paragraph: A powerful law used by New York’s top prosecutor to bring fraud charges against Wall Street firms was reined in by the state’s highest court on Tuesday, a decision that could imperil an $11 billion lawsuit against Credit Suisse and blunt a favored tool for pursuing wrongdoing by banks and their executives.

headline.main: New York’s Top Court Limits Time Frame for Martin Act Lawsuits
headline.print_headline: Court Curbs Legal Weapon In Fighting Fraud by Banks
